	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>bumbleroot</b><br /><i>Bush pursued the tax cuts as if he had a mandate. He didn't have a mandate. The American people did not give him more votes. There were more people willing to accept a Clinton/Gore continuation than not accept one. The tax cut just wasn't on everyone's mind and it wasn't a mandate.<br />
I believe I have shown on other posts that because of Bush's wavering views of the deficit he has no idea on how to do things economically. Using the same logic he uses, every company should give their employees bonuses because their profits went up. Can you understand how this would hurt a company and how they would not be able to grow their revenues? What's even worse is that the government has no other source of income other than taxes.  I have not yet seen a reasonable reason to give tax cuts back to the people other than it being a well-liked idea. Shit, I'm sure 99% of employees would vote themselves a bonus if they could- the American people would do the same thing. That doesn't mean its the right move. A tax cut is more of a popular idea than it is a sensible idea.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
We're not talking about apples and apples, Bumble. Company profits and government surplus are two completely differnt animals.<br />
<br />
Yes, as an employee I do expect raises and bonus as my work habits and production quality / level thus helps the company secure a profit. However, I cannot demand a raise, etc (unless im willing to take a hike). But the same is not true about the government and our tax dollars. You see, we have trusted those in our government to best manage and utilize tax revenues. When they mis-manage those funds, we vote them out, right? In other words, we can &quot;demand&quot; those tax dollars back if we are being over-taxed. <br />
<br />
Using your example of privately owned businesses, would you accept a deduction in pay if the company you worked for needed more money to run the operation? You wouldnt have a choice, right (other then find another job)? If you saw that it was an honest buisness move, although you wouldnt like it, you would understand. However, if your company decided to lower your pay in order to up and add to its existing profits, now you would have a problem rightfully. Well, the same holds true in government spending. If the government is wasting tax dollars, and is in debt, we may not want a tax decrease but rather an adjustment of how the dollars are being spent. If there is a considerable surplus after all the bills have been paid, well then its time to lower taxes.</p>
	
	
	
	
	
