</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Lurikeen</b><br /><i>You just stated why we should increase taxes. To eliminate debt. All of us know that is what has to be done. Do you increase your debt load at home and seek a pay cut? When you want to pay off debt faster do you throw less money at the debt?<br />
<br />
Further your disjunct is not the case. It is not one way or the other. We can (and have) cut spending and increase taxes with a good result. We don't have to spend the increased revenue on new programs.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
Sorry but let me put this to you plainly: bullshit! Bush hasn't a <i>reason</i> behind his tax cuts which is obvious from his 2001 round of tax debilitation.<br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
No it was not obvious. The economic wheel had turned. Having a surplus now would greatly strengthen the economy. We would have more money to enrich our current ailing domestic problems. Conservatives are keen on pointing out that government should be run like a business. Well, then let's run it like a business. Successful businesses aren't those in bankruptcy! In fact, successful business owners (and CEOs) understand that there must be some cash in the pot to spend at all times.<br />
<br />
Conservatives <i>really don't believe</i> government should be treated like a business. If they really believed that then they would want government to be successful and the measure of success in the private world is growth! Conservatives want government to shrink (except for the military). They want government to be anemic. <br />
<br />
<br />
<br />
I agree with you on the Office of Homeland Security. They should axe that mo fo!<br />
<br />
It is debatable as to what the government knew prior to 9/11 and if it was actionable knowledge. However, if the federal government had been working on a surplus and keeping it, then we could afford the war on terror. But another problem is even Bush is making the mistake of thinking that throwing money at a problem is the solution. People understand that spending and taxing responsibly, and with accountability, is necessary. People get pissed off when the feds aren't transparent with their spending, since it looks like they are hiding money from us!<br />
<br />
We also need to start electing politicians who aren't afraid to cut into favorite beauracracies! Why think that by cutting welfare we will get a new windfall of money? We won't, but if we eliminate a good portion of our government agencies we will see the money! We should be downsizing the &quot;corporate government&quot; starting by eliminating many of the middle management positions, and freezing hiring to allow attrition to work.<br />
<br />
Finally, if I had a wish list I could submit to congress, I would include in it getting rid of the electoral college in favor of the popular vote. Right now our Presidential candidates lobby certain states in order to get their votes. That includes wheeling and dealing with the Congressmen of those states and ensuring they are re-elected. Wheeling and dealing with the industry of those state and ensuring they get what they want. And why do they do that? Because the candidates know that money can potentially buy just enough votes to win all the electoral points for any given state. If we bring the weight of victory to the popular vote, then candidates would need to go directly to the people... not to particular states. This is a bigger issue for me than term limits which most politicians renege on any way making it worthless.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
I agree with alot of what your saying, Lurik. I do not think that <i>all</i> government surplus should be given back to taxpayers when there are many programs that need valuable dollars. However, much like a buisness, if you over-work your employees and give them less pay, your buisness will most likely suffer. This is much of what happened in the last 10 to 15 years.<br />
<br />
One example of tax code disfunction is when its more profitable for a company to be less profitable. Meaning that if they increase their profits above a certain level, that will elevate them into a new tax bracket, thus cutting deeper into profits. As a result of this taxable level, naturally one would not want to expand unless they could expand enough to compensate for the increased tax... the differnce could be 2 jobs.. or it could be 100 to 500 jobs depending on the company. Should the government give those companies a tax break and allow them to grow and thus increase their profits and taxable income? Or should the government raise taxes on that company and basically &quot;cap&quot; its profit level (which would equal less jobs, raises, etc)?</p>
	
	
	
	
	
		<div class="smallfont"><a href="report.php?s=0ec543b6de6f51f7e1a6de556279b189&amp;p=155449">Report Post</a> | IP: <a href="postings.php?s=0ec543b6de6f51f7e1a6de556279b189&amp;do=getip&amp;p=155449">Logged</a></div>
	
	<!-- / message -->
		
	</td>
