	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Rheaton</b><br /><i>Should the government give those companies a tax break and allow them to grow and thus increase their profits and taxable income? Or should the government raise taxes on that company and basically &quot;cap&quot; its profit level (which would equal less jobs, raises, etc)?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
You bring up a point that really peaves me. The government should not be in the business of providing incentives, period! If a company is afraid to grow because of taxes, then let them fall to the wayside. There are enough hungry entrepreneurs in the market who will gladly work to make not only enough money to pay the taxes, but to make an even larger profit.<br />
<br />
I think it is just wrong for government to pay farmers, for example, not to grow crops in order to regulate prices on the market. It is wrong to provide tax cuts to corporations to &quot;grow jobs&quot;. My boss doesn't give me raises because he wants me to work harder! I get raises because I have worked harder and better! Why in the hell should corporations get a tax break to grow their businesses? If you are taxed at 30%, then you should pay 30% and have absolutely no hope in hell of recovering the money! It should be treated as an expense. In fact, that would (and does) drive me to make more knowing that once I have covered that expense the rest is mine.</p>
	
	
	
