<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Lurikeen</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Pinko Commie<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Nov 2002<br />
	Location: Not here!<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Rheaton</b><br /><i>How much control should the government have over what we do? Your right in that providing incentives to certain buisnesses, while not others, is wrong. But if you cap and limit profit and expansion, you have done an even greater disservice to the revenues and employment rate.<br />
<br />
Small buisness should get the greatest tax breaks, imo. Help them get established (then cut their nuts off after they start raking in profits! )</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
<br />
Your first question encompasses much more than the business world. How much control should government have over businesses? Well, the real question isn't about <i>how much</i> control but over what <i>type</i> of control government should have. I can't give a good answer to any of those questions. What I can say is that the government ought not to provide <i>incentives</i> for growth. I am a firm believer in corporate natural selection... survival of the fitest. If your corporation needs tax breaks in order to grow, then it has been selected for extinction.<br />
<br />
Governments learn very quickly just how far they can raise taxes on business. Boeing had pretty muched ditched Washington State because our governor is an imbecile in how he taxed the hell out of them until they finally gave up and moved to a state with a much better tax rate. Which brings up an issue. If government can negotiate corporate tax rates, then they can be as unfair as possible. If we locked in a rate that was not negotiable and there was no chance in hell at recovering the tax, then I think the economy would thrive. I think it would be stronger than ever. People would know what to expect and wouldn't have to be one of the big boys wheeling and dealing with governments in order to make it.<br />
<br />
Finally, I think you are making a wrong assumption that a tax caps growth. That is not true. What &quot;caps&quot; growth is when local, state, and federal governments ride in with their tax wands and wave them over businesses willy nilly expecting them to pay. We don't need to stop taxing, we need to stop governments from <i>inventing</i> new taxes to impose on businesses.</p>
	
	
	
		<div>__________________<br /><font face="Arial"> <font color="blue"> <b><font size="3">Lurikeen Mali`Kyre </font> </font></b></font><br />
<font face="Arial"><font color="brick"><b>&lt;Drowned Legion&gt;</font></font></b><br />
