<tr>
	<td class="alt1" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Rheaton</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Registered User<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Nov 2002<br />
	
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt1" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Lurikeen</b><br /><i>Your first question encompasses much more than the business world. How much control should government have over businesses? Well, the real question isn't about <i>how much</i> control but over what <i>type</i> of control government should have. I can't give a good answer to any of those questions. What I can say is that the government ought not to provide <i>incentives</i> for growth. I am a firm believer in corporate natural selection... survival of the fitest. If your corporation needs tax breaks in order to grow, then it has been selected for extinction.<br />
<br />
Governments learn very quickly just how far they can raise taxes on business. Boeing had pretty muched ditched Washington State because our governor is an imbecile in how he taxed the hell out of them until they finally gave up and moved to a state with a much better tax rate. Which brings up an issue. If government can negotiate corporate tax rates, then they can be as unfair as possible. If we locked in a rate that was not negotiable and there was no chance in hell at recovering the tax, then I think the economy would thrive. I think it would be stronger than ever. People would know what to expect and wouldn't have to be one of the big boys wheeling and dealing with governments in order to make it.<br />
<br />
Finally, I think you are making a wrong assumption that a tax caps growth. That is not true. What &quot;caps&quot; growth is when local, state, and federal governments ride in with their tax wands and wave them over businesses willy nilly expecting them to pay. We don't need to stop taxing, we need to stop governments from <i>inventing</i> new taxes to impose on businesses.</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
The incentives knife can cut both ways. Im not sure of all the tax incentives a company receives for say payin into IRAs, insurance, etc. but I know its gotta be a good move. It allows the taxes that would otherwise be paid to come to the employee.<br />
<br />
Survival of the fitest doesnt really apply to big corporations. Those at the top are usually well to do for the rest of their days. Those who suffer are the employes. So, although the rich wanna keep getting richer, the typical &quot;little person&quot; employee should want the government to not over-tax their place of employment into extinction. Even if a business is surviving, the tax rate may be so that there isnt any room for raises and advances. Increased hours for less pay just so &quot;the man&quot; can have his (this is all too common).<br />
<br />
If the rich republican president passes a tax-cut that helps the company you work for pocket more profit, woudlnt you expect some kind of return? If its been long hours and low pay, then your company gets a tax break, and that company passes it onto you in the way of raises and more employees (thus lowering the work load on you), wouldnt that be a good thing? If the company squanded the extra savings, and upped the contribution rate to thus rich president, then yes, its a fucked up incentive. But anything that helps the American people find work, thus pumping revenues into the government for distribution as needed, its gotta be good. <br />
<br />
Too much is expected of the government, really. We may be digging ourselves a shallow grave if we demand too much intervention on their part. Bush said it straight when he was talking about the tax cuts.. &quot;Give the money back to the American people and trust that they will do whats best&quot; .. Can you argue with that?</p>
	
	
	
	
	
