<tr>
	<td class="alt2" width="175" align="center" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><b>Lurikeen</b>
<span class="smallfont">
	<br />
	Pinko Commie<br />
		
	
	<br />
	Joined: Nov 2002<br />
	Location: Not here!<br />
	
</span></td>
	
	<td class="alt2" valign="top">
	
	<!-- message -->
	<p><blockquote><span class="smallfont">Quote:</span><hr size="1" />Originally Posted by <b>Rheaton</b><br /><i>Too much is expected of the government, really. We may be digging ourselves a shallow grave if we demand too much intervention on their part. Bush said it straight when he was talking about the tax cuts.. &quot;Give the money back to the American people and trust that they will do whats best&quot; .. Can you argue with that?</i><hr size="1" /></blockquote><br />
Here we agree. Government was not meant to be the vehicle driving success in our country, but rather it is supposed to be there to ensure nothing impedes success of the individual. In fact, if we just ask the question &quot;What is business?&quot; we find that all of us are in <i>business</i> for ourselves, since we should all have a particular purpose or endeavor in the world we seek to accomplish.<br />
<br />
It is over ideas of <i>individualism</i> that I sound more libertarian. I don't want government telling me how to invest and save for my retirement. I don't want to be forced into their medical plan or disability programs when I am old. I want to have choices. I am not saying we shouldn't have government medical, disability, and retirement programs, but I don't want to be told by the feds that is what I have to have regardless of the level of personal responsibility I demonstrate. That brings taxes to the foreground of my thinking.<br />
<br />
I believe I am responsible enough to chip in to ensure schools run, roads get built and maintained and that the sick and needy have care. For example, I am not a church goer now, but when I did attend a church I paid my tithes religiously (pun intended). There wasn't a single pay check were I didn't cut my 10% off the top for God.  <img src="images/smilies/tongue.gif" border="0" alt="" title="stick out tongue" smilieid="6" />  Did my pastor have to come to me and reinterpret scripture saying God had to raise my tithe to 15%? Hell no he didn't! The church got it's 10% and that was all it was getting! Somehow, the church was able to flourish. The poor were cared for in the church. Families where the bread winners lost jobs had jobs found for them. In short, the members of the church viewed each person as an integral part of the community. What would happen if each person in America viewed each other that way?<br />
<br />
The rubber meets the road over the issue of <i>community</i> and I fear that most of us could give a rats ass what happens to the people in the next town or city over. The &quot;I&quot; generation is still alive and well and they are keen on emphasizing the &quot;I&quot; in commun<b>I</b>ty! It boils down to what <b>I</b> can get out of this government for many people. Many employers operate on how they can get the most work done for cheap. How can I ensure you fail so that I succeed?<br />
<br />
So, Bush's statement on giving back money to Americans was nothing more than catering to the &quot;I generation&quot;. Well, the &quot;I generation&quot; are not indivdualists. They are just fucking greedy. The individualist understands that governments are essential in protecting the political and economic independence of each one of us. Afterall, government is a utility that is supposed to protect our values, rights, and duties. Once government infringes upon our independence of action and thought it has gone too far! Ok... I am preaching. I will stop here.</p>
	
	
	
